nia]]. It is composed of a single village, Valea Teilor.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{GEOnet|-1174140}}\n\n{{Tulcea County}}\n\n[[Category:Communes in Tulcea County]]\n\n{{Tulcea-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valea_Teilor"}
{"title_page": "The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Painting by Vincent van Gogh}}\n{{current||art piece involved in a current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file = Van_Gogh_-_The_Parsonage_Garden_at_Nuenen.jpg\n| caption = \n| title = The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen\n| alt = \n| other_language_1 = \n| other_title_1 = \n| other_language_2 = \n| other_title_2 = \n| artist = [[Vincent van Gogh]]\n| year = {{Start date|1884|05}}\n| medium = Oil on paper on panel\n| material = \n| height_metric = 25\n| width_metric = 57\n| length_metric = \n| height_imperial = \n| width_imperial = \n| length_imperial = \n| diameter_metric = \n| diameter_imperial = \n| dimensions = \n| metric_unit = cm<!--don't leave this parameter blank\u2014either don't include it, or include the default cm. Not including it will default it to cm.-->\n| imperial_unit = in<!--don't leave this parameter blank\u2014either don't include it, or include the default in. Not including it will default it to in.-->\n| city = \n| museum = Currently unknown (stolen from the [[Singer Laren]] Museum on 30 March 2020)\n| coordinates = <!-- Only use for the exact coordinates of the artwork itself (and only where known) and not for the coordinates of the museum. Leave blank if coordinates are not known. -->\n| owner = [[Groninger Museum]]\n}}\n'''''The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen''''' ({{lang-nl|De pastorie in Nuenen}}), alternatively named '''''The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen in Spring''''' ({{lang-nl|De pastorie in Nuenen in het voorjaar}}) or '''''Spring Garden''''' ({{lang-nl|Lentetuin}}: F185, JH484), is an early oil painting by 19th-century Dutch [[Post-Impressionism|post-Impressionist]] painter [[Vincent van Gogh]], made in May 1884 while he was living with his parents in [[Nuenen]]. Van Gogh made several drawings and oil paintings of the surrounding gardens and the garden fa\u00e7ade of the parsonage.<ref name= \"Web Gallery of Art, searchable fine arts image database2\">{{cite web | title= The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen in Spring by GOGH, Vincent van | website= Web Gallery of Art | url= https://www.wga.hu/html_m/g/gogh_van/02/nuenen05.html | access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> It had been in the collection of the [[Groninger Museum]] since 1962 but was stolen on 30 March 2020 from an exhibition at the [[Singer Laren]] museum in [[Laren, North Holland]], Netherlands.<ref name=\"artnet News 2020\"/>\n\n==Background==\nVan Gogh lived in [[The Hague]] with [[Sien Hoornik]] and then alone for a few months in [[Drenthe]] in the northern Netherlands. He then went to live with his parents in the parsonage of the [[Dutch Reformed Church]] at Nuenen near [[Eindhoven]] in December 1883 where his father was pastor,<ref name=\"Route\">{{cite web | last=Route | first=Van Gogh | title=Vincent van Gogh in Nuenen, The Netherlands | website=Van Gogh Route | url=https://www.vangoghroute.com/the-netherlands/nuenen/ | access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> and they turned the laundry room into a studio for him at the back of the house.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028073701/http://www.vangoghmuseum.nl/vgm/index.jsp?page=1564&collection=619&lang=en |title=The Vicarage at Nuenen, 1885 |year=2005\u20132011 |work=Permanent Collection |publisher=Van Gogh Museum |accessdate=15 May 2011}}</ref>   \n\nHe remained with his parents in Nuenen for nearly two years making around 200 drawings and paintings, including his first major work ''[[The Potato Eaters]]''. He moved to Antwerp in November 1885<ref name=\"Van Gogh Museum\">{{cite web | title=Peasant Painter | website=Van Gogh Museum | url=https://www.vangoghmuseum.nl/en/vincent-van-gogh-life-and-work/van-goghs-life-1853-1890/peasant-painter | access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> and to Paris in 1886.<ref name=\"The New York Times 2013\">{{cite news|last=Siegal|first=Nina|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/17/arts/international/becoming-vincent-van-gogh-the-paris-years.html|title=Becoming Vincent Van Gogh: The Paris Years|date=16 October 2013|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116032131/https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/17/arts/international/becoming-vincent-van-gogh-the-paris-years.html|archive-date=16 November 2013|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nIn Nuenen, Van Gogh documented the changing seasons in his paintings of the parsonage's garden, which was enclosed by a high stone wall and included a duck pond with a boat dock, paths and hedges, flower and vegetable garden plots and an orchard.<ref>{{cite book| author=Fell, D |year=2005 |origyear=2004 |title=Van Gogh's Women: Vincent's Love Affairs and Journey Into Madness | location=New York|publisher=Carroll and Graf Publishers |page=56 | isbn=0-7432-0233-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ooSWQtDhz_AC }}</ref> \n\nPreceded by a series of wintery drawings,<ref name=\"Web Gallery of Art, searchable fine arts image database-garden1\">{{cite web | title=The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen in Winter by GOGH, Vincent van | website=Web Gallery of Art, searchable fine arts image database | url=https://www.wga.hu/html_m/g/gogh_van/17/4nuene02.html | access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> this painting was probably made in May 1884.<ref name=\"Web Gallery of Art, searchable fine arts image database2\"/> It depicts a view of the garden with a dark-clothed female figure in the foreground. In the distance are the ruins of the old church, also depicted in works such as ''[[Old Church Tower at Nuenen]]'', before it was demolished in 1885.<ref name=\"Route-Old-Church\">{{cite web | last=Route | first=Van Gogh | title=Old Church, Nuenen, The Netherlands | website=Van Gogh Route | url=https://www.vangoghroute.com/the-netherlands/nuenen/old-church/ | access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> It uses the dark palette of greens and browns, typical of Van Gogh's early works, with touches of green and red in the painting indicating that winter has passed and spring has begun.<ref name=\"van Heugten 2018 p. \">{{cite book | last=van Heugten | first=S. | title=Van Gogh and the Seasons | publisher=Princeton University Press | year=2018 | isbn=978-0-691-17971-1 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NL88DwAAQBAJ | access-date=31 March 2020 | page=}}</ref> In a letter that Van Gogh sent to [[Anthon van Rappard]] in March 1884, he mentioned the change in the seasons: \"Ben ook zoekende naar de kleur van den wintertuin. Doch die is reeds een lente tuin - nu. En is iets heel anders geworden.\" (\"Am also searching for the colour of the winter garden. But it is already a spring garden - now. And has become something completely different.\")<ref>[http://www.vangoghletters.org/vg/letters/let435/letter.html Letter 435],  on or about Saturday, 8 March 1884, vangoghletters.org</ref>\n\nThe painting is unusually wide, measuring {{cvt|25|x|57|cm|in}} without its decorative frame, exceeding [[Double-square painting|double square]].<ref name=\"Burglary\">{{cite web |title=Burglary at Singer Laren |url=https://www.singerlaren.nl/en/nieuws/460/burglary_at_singer_laren/ |publisher=Singer Laren |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Van Gogh may have worked with the help of a perspective window (a wooden frame strung with wires).<ref>[https://www.artsalonholland.nl/vincent-van-gogh/lentetuin-de-pastorietuin-te-nuenen-in-het-voorjaar Lentetuin, de pastorietuin te Nuenen in het voorjaar (1884) - Vincent van Gogh], artsalonholland.nl</ref> It had been in the collection of the [[Groninger Museum]], in the Dutch city of [[Groningen]], since 1962<ref>[https://collectie.groningermuseum.nl/Details/collect/10000525 Lentetuin, de pastorietuin te Nuenen in het voorjaar], Groninger Museum</ref> but was stolen in 2020.\n\n<gallery heights=120px caption=\"Other examples of the parsonage garden at Nuenen in Van Gogh's work\" class=\"center\">\nFile:Wintertuin, Vincent van Gogh, Nuenen, maart 1884.jpg|thumb|right|''Winter Garden'' (\"Wintertuin\"), pencil and ink drawing, March 1884, [[Van Gogh Museum]], Amsterdam (F1128, JH466)\nFile:Vincent van Gogh - The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen in Winter - Google Art Project.jpg|''The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen in Winter'', pen and ink drawing, March 1884, [[Museum of Fine Arts, Budapest]] (F1130, JH465)\nFile:Gogh - f 1133.jpg|''Parsonage Garden'', April 1884, small drawing sent to [[Anthon van Rappard]], private collection (F1188)\nFile:Van Gogh - Der alte Friedhofsturm in Nuenen.jpeg|''[[Old Church Tower at Nuenen]]'', May 1884, oil on canvas on panel, [[Foundation E.G. B\u00fchrle Collection]], Z\u00fcrich (F88, JH490)\nFile:Van Gogh - Der Pfarrgarten in Nuenen im Schnee1.jpeg|''The Parsonage Garden in Nuenen in the Snow'', oil on canvas on panel, January 1885, [[Norton Simon Museum]], Pasadena (F194, JH603)\nFile:Van Gogh - Der Pfarrgarten in Nuenen im Schnee.jpeg|''The Parsonage Garden in Nuenen in the Snow'', oil on canvas on panel, January 1885, [[Armand Hammer Museum of Art]], Los Angeles (F67, JH604)\nFile:De tuin van de pastorie te Nuenen, van Gogh, 1885.jpg|''The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen'', watercolour on paper, October/November 1885, [[Noordbrabants Museum]], [[\u2019s-Hertogenbosch]] (F1234, JH954)\nFile:Van Gogh - Der Pfarrgarten in Nuenen mit Teich und Figuren.jpeg|''The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen with Pond and Figures'', oil on panel, 1885, destroyed by fire in Rotterdam in the Second World War (F124, JH955) \n</gallery>\n\n==Theft==\nThe painting was stolen from the [[Singer Laren]] museum in [[Laren, North Holland]], on 30 March 2020, which would have been Van Gogh's 167th birthday. The museum institution was closed at the time as a result of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"artnet News 2020\">{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/thieves-stolen-van-gogh-masterpiece-dutch-museum-1819743|title=Opportunistic Thieves Just Stole a Prized Van Gogh Landscape From a Locked-Down Dutch Museum Under Cover of Night|last=Rea|first=Naomi|date=30 March 2020|website=Artnet|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331160056/https://news.artnet.com/art-world/thieves-stolen-van-gogh-masterpiece-dutch-museum-1819743|archive-date=31 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Boffey|first=Daniel|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/30/van-gogh-painting-stolen-from-dutch-museum|title=Van Gogh painting stolen from Dutch museum|date=30 March 2020|work=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401065305/https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/30/van-gogh-painting-stolen-from-dutch-museum|archive-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> The painting had been on loan from the [[Groninger Museum]].<ref name=\"artnet News 2020\"/> Police stated the thieves broke through the glass doors around 3:15 a.m. and left by the time police responded to the alarm.<ref name=\"Editorial 2020\">{{cite news|last=Verweij|first=Hilde|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-netherlands-museum-van-gogh-idUSKBN21H23M|title=Van Gogh painting stolen from Dutch museum during coronavirus shutdown|date=30 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401030932/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-netherlands-museum-van-gogh-idUSKBN21H23M|archive-date=1 April 2020|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\nMuseum director Jan Rudolph de Lorm said, \"I'm shocked and unbelievably annoyed that this has happened. This beautiful and moving painting by one of our greatest artists stolen \u2013 removed from the community\u2026 It is very bad for the Groninger Museum, it is very bad for the Singer, but it is terrible for us all because art exists to be seen and shared by us, the community, to enjoy to draw inspiration from and to draw comfort from, especially in these difficult times.\"<ref name=\"The New York Times 2020\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/30/world/europe/ap-eu-netherlands-museum-break-in.html|title=Dutch Museum Says Van Gogh Painting Stolen in Overnight Raid|date=30 March 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=30 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331211147/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/30/world/europe/ap-eu-netherlands-museum-break-in.html|archive-date=31 March 2020|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of stolen paintings]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Vincent van Gogh}}\n\n[[Category:1884 paintings]]\n[[Category:Churches in art]]\n[[Category:Landscape paintings]]\n[[Category:Lost paintings]]\n[[Category:Paintings by Vincent van Gogh]]\n[[Category:Stolen works of art]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Painting by Vincent van Gogh}}\n{{current||art piece involved in a current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox artwork\n| image_file = Van_Gogh_-_The_Parsonage_Garden_at_Nuenen.jpg\n| caption = \n| title = The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen\n| alt = \n| other_language_1 = \n| other_title_1 = \n| other_language_2 = \n| other_title_2 = \n| artist = [[Vincent van Gogh]]\n| year = {{Start date|1884|05}}\n| medium = Oil on paper on panel\n| material = \n| height_metric = 25\n| width_metric = 57\n| length_metric = \n| height_imperial = \n| width_imperial = \n| length_imperial = \n| diameter_metric = \n| diameter_imperial = \n| dimensions = \n| metric_unit = cm<!--don't leave this parameter blank\u2014either don't include it, or include the default cm. Not including it will default it to cm.-->\n| imperial_unit = in<!--don't leave this parameter blank\u2014either don't include it, or include the default in. Not including it will default it to in.-->\n| city = \n| museum = Currently unknown (stolen from the [[Singer Laren]] Museum on 30 March 2020)\n| coordinates = <!-- Only use for the exact coordinates of the artwork itself (and only where known) and not for the coordinates of the museum. Leave blank if coordinates are not known. -->\n| owner = [[Groninger Museum]]\n}}\n'''''The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen''''' ({{lang-nl|De pastorie in Nuenen}}), alternatively named '''''The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen in Spring''''' ({{lang-nl|De pastorie in Nuenen in het voorjaar}}) or '''''Spring Garden''''' ({{lang-nl|Lentetuin}}: F185, JH484), is an early oil painting by 19th-century Dutch [[Post-Impressionism|post-Impressionist]] painter [[Vincent van Gogh]], made in May 1884 while he was living with his parents in [[Nuenen]]. Van Gogh made several drawings and oil paintings of the surrounding gardens and the garden fa\u00e7ade of the parsonage.<ref name= \"Web Gallery of Art, searchable fine arts image database2\">{{cite web | title= The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen in Spring by GOGH, Vincent van | website= Web Gallery of Art | url= https://www.wga.hu/html_m/g/gogh_van/02/nuenen05.html | access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> It had been in the collection of the [[Groninger Museum]] since 1962 but was stolen on 30 March 2020 from an exhibition at the [[Singer Laren]] museum in [[Laren, North Holland]], Netherlands.<ref name=\"artnet News 2020\"/>\n\n==Background==\nVan Gogh lived in [[The Hague]] with [[Sien Hoornik]] and then alone for a few months in [[Drenthe]] in the northern Netherlands. He then went to live with his parents in the parsonage of the [[Dutch Reformed Church]] at Nuenen near [[Eindhoven]] in December 1883 where his father was pastor,<ref name=\"Route\">{{cite web | last=Route | first=Van Gogh | title=Vincent van Gogh in Nuenen, The Netherlands | website=Van Gogh Route | url=https://www.vangoghroute.com/the-netherlands/nuenen/ | access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref> and they turned the laundry room into a studio for him at the back of the house.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028073701/http://www.vangoghmuseum.nl/vgm/index.jsp?page=1564&collection=619&lang=en |title=The Vicarage at Nuenen, 1885 |year=2005\u20132011 |work=Permanent Collection |publisher=Van Gogh Museum |accessdate=15 May 2011}}</ref>   \n\nHe remained with his parents in Nuenen for nearly two years making around 200 drawings and paintings, including his first major work ''[[The Potato Eaters]]''. He moved to Antwerp in November 1885<ref name=\"Van Gogh Museum\">{{cite web | title=Peasant Painter | website=Van Gogh Museum | url=https://www.vangoghmuseum.nl/en/vincent-van-gogh-life-and-work/van-goghs-life-1853-1890/peasant-painter | access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> and to Paris in 1886.<ref name=\"The New York Times 2013\">{{cite news|last=Siegal|first=Nina|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/17/arts/international/becoming-vincent-van-gogh-the-paris-years.html|title=Becoming Vincent Van Gogh: The Paris Years|date=16 October 2013|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131116032131/https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/17/arts/international/becoming-vincent-van-gogh-the-paris-years.html|archive-date=16 November 2013|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nIn Nuenen, Van Gogh documented the changing seasons in his paintings of the parsonage's garden, which was enclosed by a high stone wall and included a duck pond with a boat dock, paths and hedges, flower and vegetable garden plots and an orchard.<ref>{{cite book| author=Fell, D |year=2005 |origyear=2004 |title=Van Gogh's Women: Vincent's Love Affairs and Journey Into Madness | location=New York|publisher=Carroll and Graf Publishers |page=56 | isbn=0-7432-0233-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ooSWQtDhz_AC }}</ref> \n\nPreceded by a series of wintery drawings,<ref name=\"Web Gallery of Art, searchable fine arts image database-garden1\">{{cite web | title=The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen in Winter by GOGH, Vincent van | website=Web Gallery of Art, searchable fine arts image database | url=https://www.wga.hu/html_m/g/gogh_van/17/4nuene02.html | access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> this painting was probably made in May 1884.<ref name=\"Web Gallery of Art, searchable fine arts image database2\"/> It depicts a view of the garden with a dark-clothed female figure in the foreground. In the distance are the ruins of the old church, also depicted in works such as ''[[Old Church Tower at Nuenen]]'', before it was demolished in 1885.<ref name=\"Route-Old-Church\">{{cite web | last=Route | first=Van Gogh | title=Old Church, Nuenen, The Netherlands | website=Van Gogh Route | url=https://www.vangoghroute.com/the-netherlands/nuenen/old-church/ | access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> It uses the dark palette of greens and browns, typical of Van Gogh's early works, with touches of green and red in the painting indicating that winter has passed and spring has begun.<ref name=\"van Heugten 2018 p. \">{{cite book | last=van Heugten | first=S. | title=Van Gogh and the Seasons | publisher=Princeton University Press | year=2018 | isbn=978-0-691-17971-1 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NL88DwAAQBAJ | access-date=31 March 2020 | page=}}</ref> In a letter that Van Gogh sent to [[Anthon van Rappard]] in March 1884, he mentioned the change in the seasons: \"Ben ook zoekende naar de kleur van den wintertuin. Doch die is reeds een lente tuin - nu. En is iets heel anders geworden.\" (\"Am also searching for the colour of the winter garden. But it is already a spring garden - now. And has become something completely different.\")<ref>[http://www.vangoghletters.org/vg/letters/let435/letter.html Letter 435],  on or about Saturday, 8 March 1884, vangoghletters.org</ref>\n\nThe painting is unusually wide, measuring {{cvt|25|x|57|cm|in}} without its decorative frame, exceeding [[Double-square painting|double square]].<ref name=\"Burglary\">{{cite web |title=Burglary at Singer Laren |url=https://www.singerlaren.nl/en/nieuws/460/burglary_at_singer_laren/ |publisher=Singer Laren |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref> Van Gogh may have worked with the help of a perspective window (a wooden frame strung with wires).<ref>[https://www.artsalonholland.nl/vincent-van-gogh/lentetuin-de-pastorietuin-te-nuenen-in-het-voorjaar Lentetuin, de pastorietuin te Nuenen in het voorjaar (1884) - Vincent van Gogh], artsalonholland.nl</ref> It had been in the collection of the [[Groninger Museum]], in the Dutch city of [[Groningen]], since 1962<ref>[https://collectie.groningermuseum.nl/Details/collect/10000525 Lentetuin, de pastorietuin te Nuenen in het voorjaar], Groninger Museum</ref> but was stolen in 2020.\n\n<gallery heights=120px caption=\"Other examples of the parsonage garden at Nuenen in Van Gogh's work\" class=\"center\">\nFile:Wintertuin, Vincent van Gogh, Nuenen, maart 1884.jpg|thumb|right|''Winter Garden'' (\"Wintertuin\"), pencil and ink drawing, March 1884, [[Van Gogh Museum]], Amsterdam (F1128, JH466)\nFile:Vincent van Gogh - The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen in Winter - Google Art Project.jpg|''The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen in Winter'', pen and ink drawing, March 1884, [[Museum of Fine Arts, Budapest]] (F1130, JH465)\nFile:Gogh - f 1133.jpg|''Parsonage Garden'', April 1884, small drawing sent to [[Anthon van Rappard]], private collection (F1188)\nFile:Van Gogh - Der alte Friedhofsturm in Nuenen.jpeg|''[[Old Church Tower at Nuenen]]'', May 1884, oil on canvas on panel, [[Foundation E.G. B\u00fchrle Collection]], Z\u00fcrich (F88, JH490)\nFile:Van Gogh - Der Pfarrgarten in Nuenen im Schnee1.jpeg|''The Parsonage Garden in Nuenen in the Snow'', oil on canvas on panel, January 1885, [[Norton Simon Museum]], Pasadena (F194, JH603)\nFile:Van Gogh - Der Pfarrgarten in Nuenen im Schnee.jpeg|''The Parsonage Garden in Nuenen in the Snow'', oil on canvas on panel, January 1885, [[Armand Hammer Museum of Art]], Los Angeles (F67, JH604)\nFile:De tuin van de pastorie te Nuenen, van Gogh, 1885.jpg|''The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen'', watercolour on paper, October/November 1885, [[Noordbrabants Museum]], [[\u2019s-Hertogenbosch]] (F1234, JH954)\nFile:Van Gogh - Der Pfarrgarten in Nuenen mit Teich und Figuren.jpeg|''The Parsonage Garden at Nuenen with Pond and Figures'', oil on panel, 1885, destroyed by fire in Rotterdam in the Second World War (F124, JH955) \n</gallery>\n\n==Theft==\nThe painting was stolen from the [[Singer Laren]] museum in [[Laren, North Holland]], on 30 March 2020 \u2013 which would have been Van Gogh's 167th birthday. The museum institution was closed at the time as a result of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\"artnet News 2020\">{{cite web|url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/thieves-stolen-van-gogh-masterpiece-dutch-museum-1819743|title=Opportunistic Thieves Just Stole a Prized Van Gogh Landscape From a Locked-Down Dutch Museum Under Cover of Night|last=Rea|first=Naomi|date=30 March 2020|website=Artnet|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331160056/https://news.artnet.com/art-world/thieves-stolen-van-gogh-masterpiece-dutch-museum-1819743|archive-date=31 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Boffey|first=Daniel|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/30/van-gogh-painting-stolen-from-dutch-museum|title=Van Gogh painting stolen from Dutch museum|date=30 March 2020|work=[[The Guardian]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401065305/https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2020/mar/30/van-gogh-painting-stolen-from-dutch-museum|archive-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> The painting had been on loan from the [[Groninger Museum]].<ref name=\"artnet News 2020\"/> Police stated the thieves broke through the glass doors around 3:15 a.m. and left by the time police responded to the alarm.<ref name=\"Editorial 2020\">{{cite news|last=Verweij|first=Hilde|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-netherlands-museum-van-gogh-idUSKBN21H23M|title=Van Gogh painting stolen from Dutch museum during coronavirus shutdown|date=30 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200401030932/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-netherlands-museum-van-gogh-idUSKBN21H23M|archive-date=1 April 2020|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref>\n\nMuseum director Jan Rudolph de Lorm said, \"I'm shocked and unbelievably annoyed that this has happened. This beautiful and moving painting by one of our greatest artists stolen \u2013 removed from the community\u2026 It is very bad for the Groninger Museum, it is very bad for the Singer, but it is terrible for us all because art exists to be seen and shared by us, the community, to enjoy to draw inspiration from and to draw comfort from, especially in these difficult times.\"<ref name=\"The New York Times 2020\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/30/world/europe/ap-eu-netherlands-museum-break-in.html|title=Dutch Museum Says Van Gogh Painting Stolen in Overnight Raid|date=30 March 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=30 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331211147/https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/03/30/world/europe/ap-eu-netherlands-museum-break-in.html|archive-date=31 March 2020|agency=[[Associated Press]]|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of stolen paintings]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Vincent van Gogh}}\n\n[[Category:1884 paintings]]\n[[Category:Churches in art]]\n[[Category:Landscape paintings]]\n[[Category:Lost paintings]]\n[[Category:Paintings by Vincent van Gogh]]\n[[Category:Stolen works of art]]\n", "name_user": "Ericoides", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTheft:comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Parsonage_Garden_at_Nuenen"}
{"title_page": "BYK Additives & Instruments", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n{{Orphan|date=June 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = BYK Additives & Instruments\n| logo = [[File:Logo BYK Additives & Instruments.png|left]]\n| caption = \n| native_name = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = de\n| type = [[Gesellschaft mit beschr\u00e4nkter Haftung (Deutschland)|GmbH]]\n| traded_as = \n| ISIN = \n| industry = Chemie\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = \n| founder = \n| defunct = \n| location_city = [[Wesel]], [[Deutschland]]\n| location_country = \n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices &c. -->\n| area_served = \n| key_people = * Dr. Christoph Schl\u00fcnken\n* Alison Avery\n* Gerd Judith\n* Matthias Kramer\n| products = \n| services = \n| revenue = about 1 [[billion|Bn.]] [[Euro|\u20ac]]<ref name=\"Unternehmensbericht 2019\">[https://www.altana.com/fileadmin/altana/press-news/corporate-report-2019/altana_corporate_report_2019.pdf Corporate Report] on altana.com</ref>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| num_employees = \n| homepage = https://www.byk.com/en\n}}\n'''BYK''' is a globally operating supplier of additives and measuring instruments.\n\nThe areas of application of BYK additives include the coatings, inks, plastics and oil/gas industries, the manufacture of care products, the manufacture of adhesives and sealants, and construction chemistry. The instruments section (BYK-Gardner GmbH) develops measuring instruments for evaluating the color, appearance and physical properties of coatings, plastics and paper surfaces.<ref name=\"Company website\">[https://www.byk.com/en/company.html Company website]  on byk.com</ref>  BYK is one of four Divisions within the [[Altana|ALTANA Group]].\n\nBYK Additives & Instruments employs around 2,300 people<ref name=\"Company website\" /> worldwide, approx. 850 of whom work in Wesel. In 2019, according to company figures, sales totaled about 1 billion euros.<ref name=\"Unternehmensbericht 2019\" /> Around 90% of sales are generated abroad, particularly in neighboring European countries, the USA and the Asian market.<ref name=\"Unternehmensbericht 2019\" />\n\n== History ==\nIn 1873 [[Heinrich Byk]] founded a chemicals factory in Berlin under his name, in which he initially produced soporific drugs. In 1917 the firm merged with the dye and tanning works to form [[Byk Gulden|Byk-Guldenwerke AG]]; the photochemical factory Ernst Lomberg was acquired subsequently. The first BYK additive for coatings came on the market in 1935. It enabled pigments to be distributed evenly in coatings. In 1962 BYK established the site in [[Wesel]], where it commenced production of paint and plastics additives. \n\nBYK has production sites in Germany ([[Wesel]], [[Kempen, Germany|Kempen]], [[Moosburg an der Isar]], [[Schkopau]] and [[Geretsried]]), in the Netherlands ([[Deventer]], [[Njiverdal]] and [[Denekamp]]), in Great Britain ([[Widnes]]), in the US ([[Wallingford (Connecticut)|Wallingford]], [[Chester]], [[Gonzales (Texas)|Gonzales]], [[Louisville (Kentucky)|Louisville]], Earth City and Pompano Beach) and in China ([[Tongling]]).\n\n== Research and development ==\nBYK invests around 8% of turnover each year in research and development \u2013 this is more than double the amount customary in the sector.<ref name=\"Unternehmensbericht 2019\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:BYK Additives and Instruments}}\n[[Category:Companies established in 1873]]\n[[Category:Companies based in North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Chemical companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Wesel (district)]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n{{Orphan|date=June 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = BYK Additives & Instruments\n| logo = [[File:Logo BYK Additives & Instruments.png|left]]\n| caption = \n| native_name = <!-- Company's name in home country language -->\n| native_name_lang = de\n| type = [[Gesellschaft mit beschr\u00e4nkter Haftung (Deutschland)|GmbH]]\n| traded_as = \n| ISIN = \n| industry = Chemie\n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| foundation = \n| founder = \n| defunct = \n| location_city = [[Wesel]], [[Deutschland]]\n| location_country = \n| locations = <!-- Number of locations, stores, offices &c. -->\n| area_served = \n| key_people = * Dr. Christoph Schl\u00fcnken\n* Alison Avery\n* Gerd Judith\n* Matthias Kramer\n| products = \n| services = \n| revenue = about 1 [[billion|Bn.]] [[Euro|\u20ac]]<ref name=\"Unternehmensbericht 2017\">[https://www.altana.de/uploads/tx_ttproducts/datasheet/ALTANA_UB_2017_d.pdf Company Report] on altana.de</ref>\n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| assets = \n| equity = \n| num_employees = \n| homepage = https://www.byk.com/en\n}}\n'''BYK''' is a globally operating supplier of additives and measuring instruments.\n\nThe areas of application of BYK additives include the coatings, inks, plastics and oil/gas industries, the manufacture of care products, the manufacture of adhesives and sealants, and construction chemistry. The instruments section (BYK-Gardner GmbH) develops measuring instruments for evaluating the color, appearance and physical properties of coatings, plastics and paper surfaces.<ref name=\"Company website\">[https://www.byk.com/en/company.html Company website]  on byk.com</ref>  BYK is one of four Divisions within the [[Altana|ALTANA Group]].\n\nBYK Additives & Instruments employs around 2,300 people<ref name=\"Company website\" /> worldwide, approx. 900 of whom work in Wesel. In 2018, according to company figures, sales totaled about 1 billion euros.<ref name=\"Unternehmensbericht 2017\" /> Around 89% of sales are generated abroad, particularly in neighboring European countries, the USA and the Asian market.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.altana.de/uploads/tx_ttproducts/datasheet/ALTANA_UB_2017_d.pdf|title=BYK Additives & Instruments - ALTANA AG|first=ALTANA|last=AG|website=www.altana.de}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 1873 [[Heinrich Byk]] founded a chemicals factory in Berlin under his name, in which he initially produced soporific drugs. In 1917 the firm merged with the dye and tanning works to form [[Byk Gulden|Byk-Guldenwerke AG]]; the photochemical factory Ernst Lomberg was acquired subsequently. The first BYK additive for coatings came on the market in 1935. It enabled pigments to be distributed evenly in coatings. In 1962 BYK established the site in [[Wesel]], where it commenced production of paint and plastics additives. \n\nBYK has production sites in Germany ([[Wesel]], [[Kempen, Germany|Kempen]], [[Moosburg an der Isar]], [[Schkopau]] and [[Geretsried]]), in the Netherlands ([[Deventer]], [[Njiverdal]] and [[Denekamp]]), in Great Britain ([[Widnes]]), in the US ([[Wallingford (Connecticut)|Wallingford]], [[Chester]], [[Gonzales (Texas)|Gonzales]], [[Louisville (Kentucky)|Louisville]], Earth City and Pompano Beach) and in China ([[Tongling]]).\n\n== Research and development ==\nBYK invests around 8% of turnover each year in research and development \u2013 this is more than double the amount customary in the sector.<ref name=\"Unternehmensbericht 2017\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:BYK Additives and Instruments}}\n[[Category:Companies established in 1873]]\n[[Category:Companies based in North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Chemical companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Wesel (district)]]\n", "name_user": "Drive2012", "label": "safe", "comment": "Change some Facts, Source Corporate Report 2019", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BYK_Additives_%26_Instruments"}
{"title_page": "Payal Dev", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|dated=October 2018|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| caption            = Payal Dev\n| name               = Payal Dev\n| image              = Payal Dev.jpg\n| image size         = \n| birth_date         = 26 February\n| birth_place        = [[Ramgarh Cantonment]] [[Jharkhand]], India\n| birth_name         = \n| death_place        = \n| yearsactive        = 2013\u2013present\n| spouse             = Aditya Dev\n| parents            = \n| children           = 1\n| occupation         = Playback singer, composer\n| website            = http://www.payaldev.com\n}}\n'''Payal Dev''' is an [[India|Indian]] playback singer and music composer who sings and composes music for Bollywood films.\nShe sang \"Ab Tohe Jane Na Doongi\" from the film ''[[Bajirao Mastani (soundtrack)|Bajirao Mastani]],''<ref>{{cite web | url=https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/music/music-reviews/Music-Review-Bajirao-Mastani/amp_articleshow/50123013.cms | title=Music Review: Bajirao Mastani - Times of India}}</ref> as well as \"Bhare Bazaar\" from ''[[Namaste England]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/bollywood/namaste-england-music-review-mannan-shaahs-album-is-enjoyable-but-devoid-of-great-recall-value-5385451.html | title=Namaste England music review: Mannan Shaah's album is enjoyable but devoid of great recall value- Entertainment News, Firstpost| date=16 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/payal-dev-thoroughly-enjoyed-singing-bhare-bazaar-118100800567_1.html | title=Payal Dev thoroughly enjoyed singing 'Bhare bazaar'| newspaper=Business Standard India| date=8 October 2018}}</ref> Dev successfully moved into songwriting when she composed the song [[Tum Hi Aana|\"Tu Hi Aana\"]] for the film ''[[Marjaavaan]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/tum-hi-aana-success-feels-magical-composer-payal-dev/1663572|title=''Tum hi aana'' success feels magical: Composer Payal Dev|date=15 November 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/entertainment/editorial/news/200108-tum-hi-aana-makes-me-feel-lucky-composer|title=Tum Hi Aana makes me feel lucky as a composer Payal Dev|date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n[https://www.lyricsgoo.com/genda-phool-badshah/ Genda Phool Lyrics By Badshah And Payal Dev]\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\"| \n| Denotes films that have not yet been released\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \n! style=\"background:#cfc; text-align:center;\"|'''Year''' \n! style=\"background:#cfc; text-align:center;\"|'''Film''' \n! style=\"background:#cfc; text-align:center;\"|'''Songs''' \n! style=\"background:#cfc; text-align:center;\"|'''Co-Singers'''\n! style=\"background:#cfc; text-align:center;\"|'''Composers'''\n! style=\"background:#cfc; text-align:center;\"|'''Languages'''\n! style=\"background:#cfc; text-align:center;\"|'''Notes'''\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2013 || ''[[Mai (2013 film)|Mai]]'' || \"Learn To Adjust\" || [[Arjun Kanungo]] || Nitin Shankar\n|rowspan=4|Hindi ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|''Navratri Mananey Aao Bhakton Maa Kaatyayani Ke Dware'' || \"Jagdamba Sherawali\" \n|rowspan=2|Solo \n|rowspan=2|[[Sanjeev\u2013Darshan]]|| \n|-\n| \"Meri Maiya Kaatyayani\" (Female Version)|| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2015 || rowspan=\"3\"|''[[Bajirao Mastani]]'' || \"Ab Tohe Jane Na Doongi\" || Shreyas Puranik || rowspan=\"3\" |[[Sanjay Leela Bhansali]] ||\n|-\n| \"Mannan Thirumbum Naaladi\" || Deepti Rege, Archana Gore, Pragati Joshi, Arun Ingle, Kaustubh Datar, Mani Iyer || Tamil || \n|-\n| \"Jayebheri\" || Shashi Suman, Kunal Pandit, Prithvi Gandharv, Rashi Raagga, Gitika Manjrekar, Kanika Joshi || Telugu ||\n|-\n| rowspan=6|2016 || ''Cute Kameena'' || \"Twinkle Twinkle\" || Arghya Banerjee ||[[Krsna Solo]] ||rowspan=4|Hindi ||\n|-\n|| ''[[Great Grand Mast]]'' || \"Lipstick Laga Ke\" || 