{"title_page": "2020 Caribbean earthquake", "text_new": "{{Use Jamaican English|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Earthquake between Jamaica and Cuba}}\n{{Infobox earthquake\n| name = 2020 Caribbean earthquake\n| image = 2020-01-28 Lucea, Jamaica M7.7 earthquake shakemap (USGS).jpg\n| alt =\n| caption =Shakemap from [[USGS]]\n| map =\n| map_alt =\n| map_caption =\n| pushpin_map = <!-- as per Template:Location map -->\n| map2 = {{Location map | Caribbean\n | relief             = yes\n | label              =\n | lat                = 19.419\n | long               = -78.756\n | mark               = Bullseye1.png\n | marksize           = 40\n | position           = top\n | width              = 250\n | float              = right\n | caption            =}}\n| pre-1900 = no\n| timestamp = 2020-01-28 19:10:24\n| isc-event = 617210084\n| anss-url = us60007idc\n| local-date = {{Start date|2020|01|28|df=y}}\n| local-time = 14:10:25\n| duration =\n| magnitude = 7.7 {{M|w|link=y}}<ref name=ANSS>{{ Cite anss | Cayman Trough | 2020 | us60007idc | M 7.7 - 125km NNW of Lucea, Jamaica | access-date=28 January 2020 | mode=cs1 }}</ref>\n| depth = {{convert|14.9|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| location = {{coord|19.419|N|78.756|W|region:JM_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| fault = [[Septentrional-Oriente fault zone]]\n| type = [[Strike-slip]]\n| affected = [[Cayman Islands]] <br> [[Jamaica]] <br> [[Cuba]]\n| damages =\n| intensity = [[Modified Mercalli intensity scale|VI (''Strong'')]]\n| pga = <!-- NN ''[[Peak ground acceleration|g]]'' -->\n| pgv = <!-- NN cm/s -->\n| tsunami = {{convert|1.5|ft|m|2|abbr=on|order=flip}} at [[George Town, Cayman Islands]]\n| landslide = \n| foreshocks =\n| aftershocks = Up to 6.1 {{M|w|link=y}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6474050/earthquake-cuba-jamaica/ |title=6.1-magnitude tremor follows 7.7-magnitude earthquake between Cuba and Jamaica |website=Global News |language=en|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n| casualties =\n| engvar = en-JM\n| citations =\n}}\nAt 2:10 p.m. local time ([[UTC-5]]) on 28 January 2020, an [[earthquake]] of 7.7 {{M|w|link=yes}} struck on the north side of the [[Cayman Trough]], north of [[Jamaica]] and west of the southern tip of [[Cuba]], with the epicenter being 80 miles (130 km) ESE of [[Cayman Brac]], [[Cayman Islands]] <ref name=\"HMCI_location\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.caymanprepared.ky/portal/page/portal/hmchome/pressroom/Press%20Releases%202020/Earthquake%20Update%202 |title=Earthquake Tsunami Update |last=Cayman Prepared |date=28 January 2020 |website=Cayman Islands National Emergency Website |access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> or 83 miles (134 km) north of [[Montego Bay]], [[Jamaica]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/73-magnitude-earthquake-strikes-north-jamaica/story?id=68591879 |title=Powerful earthquake strikes between Jamaica and Cuba |last=Allen |first=Karma |website=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=28 January 2020 |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Schools in Jamaica and buildings in [[Miami]] were evacuated after shaking was observed in parts of the U.S. state of Florida.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/28/americas/earthquake-caribbean-sea/index.html |title=Tsunami threat message issued after magnitude 7.7 earthquake off the coast of Jamaica |last1=Almasy |first1=Steve |last2=Eshchenko |date=28 January 2020 |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/jamaica-earthquake-today-magnitude-tsunami-warning-latest-a9306991.html |title=Jamaica earthquake: Huge 7.7-magnitude tremor hits off island's coast |last=Dalton |first=Jane |date=28 January 2020 |website=[[The Independent|independent.co.uk]] |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Light shaking was also reported on the [[Yucatan peninsula]] in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/01/28/caribbean-sea-earthquake-jamaica-cuba-cayman-islands/4599701002/ |title=Powerful 7.7 earthquake strikes in Caribbean between Cuba and Jamaica |last=Rice |first=Doyle |website=[[USA Today]] |date=28 January 2020 |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> It is the largest earthquake in the Caribbean since [[1946 Dominican Republic earthquake|1946]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/weather/2020/01/28/earthquake-jamaica-cuba/ |title=7.7-magnitude earthquake strikes between Jamaica and Cuba, one of the strongest on record in Caribbean |last1=Cappucci |first1=Matthew |last2=Samenow |first2=Jason |date=28 January 2020 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |url-access=limited |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> A [[tsunami]] warning for the Caribbean Sea was issued by the [[Pacific Tsunami Warning Center]] and later withdrawn.<ref>{{cite news |date=28 January 2020 |title=Caribbean earthquake of 7.7 prompts office evacuations in Miami |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-51287493 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Tectonic setting ==\nThe eastern part of the Cayman Trough forms part of the [[Gon\u00e2ve Microplate]], which lies between the [[North American Plate]] and the [[Caribbean Plate]]. It is bounded to both north and south by large [[transform fault]]s that together accommodate the relative displacement of the two major plates. To the north the boundary is the western part of the [[Septentrional-Oriente fault zone]], which accommodates 6\u201311 mm per year of plate boundary motion, while to the south the boundary is formed by the [[Walton fault zone]] to the west of Jamaica and the [[Enriquillo\u2013Plantain Garden fault zone]] to the east, accommodating about 8 mm per year.<ref name=\"DeMets\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1365-246X.2006.03236.x|last=DeMets|first=C.|author2=Wiggins-Grandison W.|year=2007|title=Deformation of Jamaica and motion of the Gon\u00e2ve microplate from GPS and seismic data|journal=[[Geophysical Journal International]]|volume=168|issue=1|pages=362\u2013378|url=http://www.mona.uwi.edu/earthquake/files/DeformJaGPS2007.pdf|accessdate=7 December 2011|bibcode = 2007GeoJI.168..362D }}</ref>\n\n==Earthquake==\nThe earthquake had a magnitude of 7.7 {{M|ww}} and an estimated depth of {{convert|14.8|km|mi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=ANSS/> The [[focal mechanism]], combined with an analysis of seismic waveforms, is consistent with strike-slip motion on the Septentrional-Oriente fault zone.<ref name=ANSS_FF>{{ short-anss | Cayman Trough | 2020| sub-title= Finite Fault | sub-url= finite-fault | February 6, 2020 }}</ref> The mainshock was followed by a series of [[aftershock]]s, with the largest being a 6.1 {{M|ww}} event that occurred less than three hours later, to the southeast of Grand Cayman.<ref>{{ Cite anss | Cayman Trough | 2020b | us60007iig | M 6.1 - 57km SE of East End, Cayman Islands | access-date=February 6, 2020 | mode=cs1 }}</ref> The modelled rupture zone extends from just west of the epicenter of the M 6.1 aftershock to just east of the mainshock epicenter, suggesting unilateral westward propagation.<ref name=ANSS_FF/>\nhi\n\n==Impact==\n===Cayman Islands===\nThere were cracked roads and many sinkholes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/jamaica-earthquake-live-updates-today-cuba-tsunami-haiti-honduras-latest-a9307001.html |title=Jamaica earthquake - live updates: Caribbean rocked by huge tremor near Cuba, with buildings evacuated in parts of US |last=Mindock |first=Clark |date=28 January 2020 |website=[[The Independent|independent.co.uk]] |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> A minor tsunami of 0.46 m or 1.5ft was recorded.<ref name=\"HMCI_timeline\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.caymanprepared.ky/portal/page/portal/hmchome/pressroom/Press%20Releases%202020/Communications%20Timeline |title=Earthquake Communications Timeline |last=Cayman Prepared |date=29 January 2020 |website=Cayman Islands National Emergency Website |access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> All government schools were closed to allow inspections for possible damage, but they were all reopened on January 30 as no major damage had been found that related to the earthquake.<ref name=\"HMCI\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.caymanprepared.ky/portal/page/portal/hmchome/pressroom/Press%20Releases%202020/Schools%20Reopen |title=Government Schools Reopen |last=Cayman Prepared |date=January 29, 2020 |website=Cayman Islands National Emergency Website |access-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Jamaica===\nA six-story building on the [[Mona, Jamaica|Mona]] campus of the [[University of the West Indies]], containing approximately 300 students, was evacuated.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/jamaica-earthquake-live-updates-today-cuba-tsunami-haiti-honduras-latest-a9307001.html |title=Tsunami warning after Jamaica hit by 7.7 magnitude earthquake - follow live |date=28 January 2020 |website=The Independent |language=en|access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Damage was reported from at least two [[Parishes of Jamaica|parishes]] in [[Cornwall County, Jamaica|western Jamaica]].<ref name=\"ODPEM_29_01\">{{Cite web |url=https://odpem.org.jm/odpem_in_the_media/7-7-magnitude-earthquake-off-the-shores-of-cuba/ |title=7.7 Magnitude Earthquake Off The Shores of Cuba |date=January 29, 2020 |publisher=Office of Disaster Preparedness and Emergency Management |access-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral buildings in and around the New Kingston vicinity were evacuated promptly after the earthquake, with several reports of shaking. The area was virtually shut down.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n===Cuba===\nTremors were felt on the southern coast of the island. A spokesman for [[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base]] stated that there were no reports of damages or injuries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wpbf.com/article/earthquake-strikes-off-coasts-of-cuba-jamaica/30692204 |title=7.7 magnitude earthquake strikes between Cuba and Jamaica |last=Press |first=The Associated |date=29 January 2020 |website=WPBF |language=en|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> [[Granma Province]] was affected by the strongest shaking, being closest to the epicenter. A survey carried out by the National Center for Seismological Research, found that one house had completely collapsed and another 300 showed some damage. The houses affected were all ones that were not in good condition before the earthquake. Damage was also reported from some schools and daycare centers.<ref name=\"On_Cuba_News_4_02\">{{Cite news |url=https://oncubanews.com/en/cuba/earthquake-damaged-buildings-in-cuba-were-in-poor-condition/ |title=Earthquake-damaged buildings in Cuba were in \u201cpoor condition\u201d |last=OnCuba Staff |date=February 4, 2020 |work=On Cuba News |access-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nTremors were felt throughout southern Florida and several buildings were evacuated, particularly in [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Miami-Dade County]] (450 miles away) and the [[Florida Keys]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcmiami.com/news/local/powerful-earthquake-reported-between-cuba-and-jamaica-usgs/2182881/ |title=Miami Buildings Shake After Powerful Earthquake Between Cuba and Jamaica |website=NBC 6 South Florida |language=en-US|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> Several government buildings in [[Downtown Miami]] were evacuated, initially on a volunteer basis until a full evacuation was ordered by the local fire department.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Charles |first1=Jacqueline |last2=Torres |first2=Nora G\u00e1mez |last3=Ocasio |first3=Bianca Padr\u00f3 |date=28 January 2020 |title=Powerful Caribbean earthquake shakes buildings in Jamaica, Cuba \u2014 even downtown Miami |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/article239725568.html |work=[[Miami Herald]] |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[2020 in the Caribbean]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in North America]]\n*[[2010 Haiti earthquake]]\n*[[2019-20 Puerto Rico earthquakes]]\n*[[List of earthquakes in 2020]]\n*[[2020s]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Earthquakes in 2020}}\n{{Earthquakes in the Caribbean}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n\n\n[[Category:2020 earthquakes|Jamaica]]\n[[Category:2020 in Jamaica]]\n[[Category:2020 in Cuba]]\n[[Category:Earthquakes in Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Earthquakes in Cuba]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in North America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Jamaican English|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Earthquake between Jamaica and Cuba}}\n{{Infobox earthquake\n| name = 2020 Caribbean earthquake\n| image = 2020-01-28 Lucea, Jamaica M7.7 earthquake shakemap (USGS).jpg\n| alt =\n| caption =Shakemap from [[USGS]]\n| map =\n| map_alt =\n| map_caption =\n| pushpin_map = <!-- as per Template:Location map -->\n| map2 = {{Location map | Caribbean\n | relief             = yes\n | label              =\n | lat                = 19.419\n | long               = -78.756\n | mark               = Bullseye1.png\n | marksize           = 40\n | position           = top\n | width              = 250\n | float              = right\n | caption            =}}\n| pre-1900 = no\n| timestamp = 2020-01-28 19:10:24\n| isc-event = 617210084\n| anss-url = us60007idc\n| local-date = {{Start date|2020|01|28|df=y}}\n| local-time = 14:10:25\n| duration =\n| magnitude = 7.7 {{M|w|link=y}}<ref name=ANSS>{{ Cite anss | Cayman Trough | 2020 | us60007idc | M 7.7 - 125km NNW of Lucea, Jamaica | access-date=28 January 2020 | mode=cs1 }}</ref>\n| depth = {{convert|14.9|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| location = {{coord|19.419|N|78.756|W|region:JM_type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| fault = [[Septentrional-Oriente fault zone]]\n| type = [[Strike-slip]]\n| affected = [[Cayman Islands]] <br> [[Jamaica]] <br> [[Cuba]]\n| damages =\n| intensity = [[Modified Mercalli intensity scale|VI (''Strong'')]]\n| pga = <!-- NN ''[[Peak ground acceleration|g]]'' -->\n| pgv = <!-- NN cm/s -->\n| tsunami = {{convert|1.5|ft|m|2|abbr=on|order=flip}} at [[George Town, Cayman Islands]]\n| landslide = \n| foreshocks =\n| aftershocks = Up to 6.1 {{M|w|link=y}}<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6474050/earthquake-cuba-jamaica/ |title=6.1-magnitude tremor follows 7.7-magnitude earthquake between Cuba and Jamaica |website=Global News |language=en|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n| casualties =\n| engvar = en-JM\n| citations =\n}}\nAt 2:10 p.m. local time ([[UTC-5]]) on 28 January 2020, an [[earthquake]] of 7.7 {{M|w|link=yes}} struck on the north side of the [[Cayman Trough]], north of [[Jamaica]] and west of the southern tip of [[Cuba]], with the epicenter being 80 miles (130 km) ESE of [[Cayman Brac]], [[Cayman Islands]] <ref name=\"HMCI_location\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.caymanprepared.ky/portal/page/portal/hmchome/pressroom/Press%20Releases%202020/Earthquake%20Update%202 |title=Earthquake Tsunami Update |last=Cayman Prepared |date=28 January 2020 |website=Cayman Islands National Emergency Website |access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> or 83 miles (134 km) north of [[Montego Bay]], [[Jamaica]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/73-magnitude-earthquake-strikes-north-jamaica/story?id=68591879 |title=Powerful earthquake strikes between Jamaica and Cuba |last=Allen |first=Karma |website=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] |date=28 January 2020 |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Schools in Jamaica and buildings in [[Miami]] were evacuated after shaking was observed in parts of the U.S. state of Florida.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/01/28/americas/earthquake-caribbean-sea/index.html |title=Tsunami threat message issued after magnitude 7.7 earthquake off the coast of Jamaica |last1=Almasy |first1=Steve |last2=Eshchenko |date=28 January 2020 |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/jamaica-earthquake-today-magnitude-tsunami-warning-latest-a9306991.html |title=Jamaica earthquake: Huge 7.7-magnitude tremor hits off island's coast |last=Dalton |first=Jane |date=28 January 2020 |website=[[The Independent|independent.co.uk]] |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Light shaking was also reported on the [[Yucatan peninsula]] in [[Mexico]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/01/28/caribbean-sea-earthquake-jamaica-cuba-cayman-islands/4599701002/ |title=Powerful 7.7 earthquake strikes in Caribbean between Cuba and Jamaica |last=Rice |first=Doyle |website=[[USA Today]] |date=28 January 2020 |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> It is the largest earthquake in the Caribbean since [[1946 Dominican Republic earthquake|1946]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/weather/2020/01/28/earthquake-jamaica-cuba/ |title=7.7-magnitude earthquake strikes between Jamaica and Cuba, one of the strongest on record in Caribbean |last1=Cappucci |first1=Matthew |last2=Samenow |first2=Jason |date=28 January 2020 |website=[[The Washington Post]] |url-access=limited |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> A [[tsunami]] warning for the Caribbean Sea was issued by the [[Pacific Tsunami Warning Center]] and later withdrawn.<ref>{{cite news |date=28 January 2020 |title=Caribbean earthquake of 7.7 prompts office evacuations in Miami |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-51287493 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Tectonic setting ==\nThe eastern part of the Cayman Trough forms part of the [[Gon\u00e2ve Microplate]], which lies between the [[North American Plate]] and the [[Caribbean Plate]]. It is bounded to both north and south by large [[transform fault]]s that together accommodate the relative displacement of the two major plates. To the north the boundary is the western part of the [[Septentrional-Oriente fault zone]], which accommodates 6\u201311 mm per year of plate boundary motion, while to the south the boundary is formed by the [[Walton fault zone]] to the west of Jamaica and the [[Enriquillo\u2013Plantain Garden fault zone]] to the east, accommodating about 8 mm per year.<ref name=\"DeMets\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1365-246X.2006.03236.x|last=DeMets|first=C.|author2=Wiggins-Grandison W.|year=2007|title=Deformation of Jamaica and motion of the Gon\u00e2ve microplate from GPS and seismic data|journal=[[Geophysical Journal International]]|volume=168|issue=1|pages=362\u2013378|url=http://www.mona.uwi.edu/earthquake/files/DeformJaGPS2007.pdf|accessdate=7 December 2011|bibcode = 2007GeoJI.168..362D }}</ref>\n\n==Earthquake==\nThe earthquake had a magnitude of 7.7 {{M|ww}} and an estimated depth of {{convert|14.8|km|mi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=ANSS/> The [[focal mechanism]], combined with an analysis of seismic waveforms, is consistent with strike-slip motion on the Septentrional-Oriente fault zone.<ref name=ANSS_FF>{{ short-anss | Cayman Trough | 2020| sub-title= Finite Fault | sub-url= finite-fault | February 6, 2020 }}</ref> The mainshock was followed by a series of [[aftershock]]s, with the largest being a 6.1 {{M|ww}} event that occurred less than three hours later, to the southeast of Grand Cayman.<ref>{{ Cite anss | Cayman Trough | 2020b | us60007iig | M 6.1 - 57km SE of East End, Cayman Islands | access-date=February 6, 2020 | mode=cs1 }}</ref> The modelled rupture zone extends from just west of the epicenter of the M 6.1 aftershock to just east of the mainshock epicenter, suggesting unilateral westward propagation.<ref name=ANSS_FF/>\n\n==Impact==\n===Cayman Islands===\nThere were cracked roads and many sinkholes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/jamaica-earthquake-live-updates-today-cuba-tsunami-haiti-honduras-latest-a9307001.html |title=Jamaica earthquake - live updates: Caribbean rocked by huge tremor near Cuba, with buildings evacuated in parts of US |last=Mindock |first=Clark |date=28 January 2020 |website=[[The Independent|independent.co.uk]] |access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> A minor tsunami of 0.46 m or 1.5ft was recorded.<ref name=\"HMCI_timeline\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.caymanprepared.ky/portal/page/portal/hmchome/pressroom/Press%20Releases%202020/Communications%20Timeline |title=Earthquake Communications Timeline |last=Cayman Prepared |date=29 January 2020 |website=Cayman Islands National Emergency Website |access-date=25 February 2020}}</ref> All government schools were closed to allow inspections for possible damage, but they were all reopened on January 30 as no major damage had been found that related to the earthquake.<ref name=\"HMCI\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.caymanprepared.ky/portal/page/portal/hmchome/pressroom/Press%20Releases%202020/Schools%20Reopen |title=Government Schools Reopen |last=Cayman Prepared |date=January 29, 2020 |website=Cayman Islands National Emergency Website |access-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Jamaica===\nA six-story building on the [[Mona, Jamaica|Mona]] campus of the [[University of the West Indies]], containing approximately 300 students, was evacuated.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/jamaica-earthquake-live-updates-today-cuba-tsunami-haiti-honduras-latest-a9307001.html |title=Tsunami warning after Jamaica hit by 7.7 magnitude earthquake - follow live |date=28 January 2020 |website=The Independent |language=en|access-date=28 January 2020}}</ref> Damage was reported from at least two [[Parishes of Jamaica|parishes]] in [[Cornwall County, Jamaica|western Jamaica]].<ref name=\"ODPEM_29_01\">{{Cite web |url=https://odpem.org.jm/odpem_in_the_media/7-7-magnitude-earthquake-off-the-shores-of-cuba/ |title=7.7 Magnitude Earthquake Off The Shores of Cuba |date=January 29, 2020 |publisher=Office of Disaster Preparedness and Emergency Management |access-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral buildings in and around the New Kingston vicinity were evacuated promptly after the earthquake, with several reports of shaking. The area was virtually shut down.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n===Cuba===\nTremors were felt on the southern coast of the island. A spokesman for [[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base]] stated that there were no reports of damages or injuries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wpbf.com/article/earthquake-strikes-off-coasts-of-cuba-jamaica/30692204 |title=7.7 magnitude earthquake strikes between Cuba and Jamaica |last=Press |first=The Associated |date=29 January 2020 |website=WPBF |language=en|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> [[Granma Province]] was affected by the strongest shaking, being closest to the epicenter. A survey carried out by the National Center for Seismological Research, found that one house had completely collapsed and another 300 showed some damage. The houses affected were all ones that were not in good condition before the earthquake. Damage was also reported from some schools and daycare centers.<ref name=\"On_Cuba_News_4_02\">{{Cite news |url=https://oncubanews.com/en/cuba/earthquake-damaged-buildings-in-cuba-were-in-poor-condition/ |title=Earthquake-damaged buildings in Cuba were in \u201cpoor condition\u201d |last=OnCuba Staff |date=February 4, 2020 |work=On Cuba News |access-date=February 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===United States===\nTremors were felt throughout southern Florida and several buildings were evacuated, particularly in [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Miami-Dade County]] (450 miles away) and the [[Florida Keys]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nbcmiami.com/news/local/powerful-earthquake-reported-between-cuba-and-jamaica-usgs/2182881/ |title=Miami Buildings Shake After Powerful Earthquake Between Cuba and Jamaica |website=NBC 6 South Florida |language=en-US|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref> Several government buildings in [[Downtown Miami]] were evacuated, initially on a volunteer basis until a full evacuation was ordered by the local fire department.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Charles |first1=Jacqueline |last2=Torres |first2=Nora G\u00e1mez |last3=Ocasio |first3=Bianca Padr\u00f3 |date=28 January 2020 |title=Powerful Caribbean earthquake shakes buildings in Jamaica, Cuba \u2014 even downtown Miami |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/article239725568.html |work=[[Miami Herald]] |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Div col}}\n*[[2020 in the Caribbean]]\n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in North America]]\n*[[2010 Haiti earthquake]]\n*[[2019-20 Puerto Rico earthquakes]]\n*[[List of earthquakes in 2020]]\n*[[2020s]]\n{{End div col}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Earthquakes in 2020}}\n{{Earthquakes in the Caribbean}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n\n\n[[Category:2020 earthquakes|Jamaica]]\n[[Category:2020 in Jamaica]]\n[[Category:2020 in Cuba]]\n[[Category:Earthquakes in Jamaica]]\n[[Category:Earthquakes in Cuba]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in North America]]\n", "name_user": "81.106.245.132", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarthquake)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Caribbean_earthquake"}
{"title_page": "Steve Schewel", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician, businessman, and academic}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = PIC Mayor Steve Schewel.jpg\n| order = \n| office = [[List of mayors of Durham, North Carolina|Mayor of Durham, North Carolina]]\n| term_start = 2017\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Bill Bell (mayor)|Bill Bell]]\n| successor = \n| office2 = Durham City Councilman\n| term_start2 = 2011\n| term_end2 = 2017\n| office3 = Vice Chair of the [[Durham Public Schools|Durham Public School Board]]\n| term_start3 = 2004\n| term_end3= 2008\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1951}}\n| birth_place = [[Lynchburg, Virginia]], US\n| alma_mater = [[Duke University]] <small>([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])</small><br>[[Columbia University]] <small>([[Master of Arts|M.A.]])</small><br>[[Duke University]] <small>([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])</small>\n| profession = politician, academic, businessman\n| spouse = Lao Rubert\n| children = 2\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n}}\n\n'''Steve Schewel''' (born 1951) is an American politician, businessman, and academic. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he is the current [[List of mayors of Durham, North Carolina|Mayor]] of [[Durham, North Carolina]] and formerly served on the Durham City Council and as the Vice Chair of the [[Durham Public Schools|Durham Public School Board]]. Schewel is also a faculty member at [[Duke University]]'s [[Sanford School of Public Policy]] and a former faculty member at [[North Carolina Central University]]. He founded the weekly newspaper ''[[Indy Week]]'' in 1983, and served as its president until he sold the paper in 2012. In 2010 he co-founded the [[Hopscotch Music Festival]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSchewel grew up in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]]. He moved to North Carolina in 1969 to attend [[Duke University]]. While an undergraduate student, Schewel served as the president of the Associated Students of Duke University. In this capacity, he granted the charter to Duke's first [[LGBTQ]] student organization in 1973.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dukespace.lib.duke.edu/dspace/bitstream/handle/10161/7853/Liggett_Middlesworth-Paper.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |title=Divergent Priorities, Diverging Visions:Lesbian Separatist versus Gay Male Integrationist Ideology surrounding Duke in the 1970s and 80s |date=2013 |website=dukespace.lib.duke.edu |format=PDF|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> He graduated [[magna cum laude]] from Duke in 1973.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanford.duke.edu/people/faculty/schewel-stephen|title=Schewel, Stephen &#124; Duke University Sanford School of Public Policy|website=sanford.duke.edu}}</ref> He earned a master's degree in English from [[Columbia University]] in 1974, and a Ph.D. in education from Duke in 1982.<ref name= hart/>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Business and academia ===\nIn 1983 Schewel founded the newspaper ''[[Indy Week|North Carolina Independent]]'', later renamed ''Indy Week''.<ref name=\"UNC library\">{{cite web|title=Collection Number 05319: Independent Weekly Records, 1982-2004|url=http://www.lib.unc.edu/mss/inv/i/Independent_Weekly.html|work=Louis Round Wilson Special Collections Library|publisher=[[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]|accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref> Schewel personally wrote the state's first [[same-sex marriage]] announcement in the paper.<ref name= steved/> Schewel stepped down as the paper's publisher in 1999, but continued on as president of the company until he sold it in 2012.<ref name= hart/> He is also a co-founder of the [[Hopscotch Music Festival]], which he sold in 2015.<ref name= hart/>\n\nSchewel is a visiting assistant professor at [[Duke University]]\u2019s [[Sanford School of Public Policy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldsun.com/news/politics-government/election/article183337776.html|title=Steve Schewel to be Durham\u2019s next mayor|last=Baumgartner Vaughan|first=Dawn|date=2017-11-07|work=The Herald-Sun|access-date=2019-12-28|url-status=live|last2=Eanes|first2=Zachery|last3=Johnson|first3=Joe}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://durhamnc.gov/1329/About-the-Mayor|title=Stephen M. Schewel &#124; Durham, NC|website=durhamnc.gov}}</ref> He is also a former [[Durham Public Schools]] board of education member and former English instructor at [[North Carolina Central University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stevefordurham.com/meet-steve|title=Meet Steve|website=Steve Schewel for Durham|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\nFrom 2004 to 2008 Schewel was a member, and Vice-Chair, of the [[Durham Public Schools]] Board of Education. He was elected to the Durham City Council in 2011 and served until 2017.<ref name= hart/> While serving on the city council, Schewel was an outspoken critic of [[North Carolina Amendment 1]] and introduced a city resolution to support [[marriage equality]]. He and his wife hosted a fundraiser at their home, raising over $200,000 to assist organizations fighting against the amendment.<ref name= steved>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stevefordurham.com/lgbtq-rights|title=LGBTQ Rights|website=Steve Schewel for Durham}}</ref>\n\nSchewel was [[2017 Durham mayoral election|elected mayor of Durham]] on November 7, 2017, to succeed the retiring [[Bill Bell (mayor)|Bill Bell]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wral.com/councilman-to-succeed-bell-as-durham-mayor/17098449/|title=Councilman to succeed Bell as Durham mayor :|last=|first=|date=2017-11-07|website=WRAL.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> After being sworn-in as mayor, Schewel spoke about hopes for [[gun control]] and environmental regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indyweek.com/api/content/0c23b601-f6fc-557c-9a87-15df12b9747b/|title=Six Months After Becoming Durham\u2019s Mayor, Steve Schewel Has a Lot to Say|first=Sarah|last=Willets|date=May 23, 2018|website=INDY Week}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2018 Schewel presided over the Jewish Baccalaureate Service at Duke University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://today.duke.edu/2018/05/durham-mayor-steve-schewel-addresses-jewish-baccalaureate-service|title=Durham Mayor Steve Schewel Addresses Jewish Baccalaureate Service|website=today.duke.edu}}</ref> In 2018 he participated in [[Michael Bloomberg]]'s Harvard City Leadership Initiative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytarheel.com/article/2020/03/bloomberg-local-nc-official-support|title=Bloomberg garners high-profile N.C. endorsements going into crucial Super Tuesday|website=The Daily Tar Heel}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 Schewel joined local business leaders and the city's fire chief to address the state of industry in Durham after the [[2019 Durham gas explosion]], which affected multiple local businesses in the [[Bright Leaf Historic District]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc11.com/5264284/|title=Mayor encourages Durham residents to support local business after deadly explosion|date=April 22, 2019|website=ABC11 Raleigh-Durham}}</ref> Schewel had arrived on the scene shortly after the explosion took place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indyweek.com/api/content/c350e0d2-6060-11e9-953a-12f1225286c6/|title=Here\u2019s What We Know\u2014And Don\u2019t Know\u2014About the Explosion That Shook Downtown Durham Last Week|first=Sarah|last=Willets|date=April 16, 2019|website=INDY Week}}</ref>\n\nSchewel proposed a $95 million housing bond in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/11/durham-candidates-election-city-council-mayor-municipal|title=A guide to the Durham city council and mayor candidates for Tuesday's municipal election|website=The Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020 Schewel stated that the city intends to help fund the mitigation of carbon monoxide issues at McDougald Terrace, a public housing complex in Durham that had to evacuate its residents due to a carbon monoxide leak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc11.com/5823431/|title='It's become more urgent': Durham mayor Steve Schewel to shuffle funding for McDougald Terrace|date=January 8, 2020|website=ABC11 Raleigh-Durham}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020 Schewel was criticized by members of the [[Israel lobby in the United States]] for supporting a municipal resolution banning police training in Israel for Durham police officers. Schewel banned the program after it was alleged that the program provided military-style training and encouraged racial violence against [[African-American]] communities.<ref name= wrcbtv/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thetower.org/6641-the-israel-resolution/|title=\"The Israel Resolution\"|date=September 12, 2018|website=The Tower}}</ref><ref name=\"Vaughan 2018\">{{cite web | last=Vaughan | first=Dawn Baumgartner | title=Bull City Politics: Jewish leaders tell council member, take Israel out of statement | website=heraldsun | date=2018-10-02 | url=https://www.heraldsun.com/news/local/counties/durham-county/article219365335.html | access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\nThe ban, approved in April 2018, forbids members of the [[Durham Police Department]] from engaging in international training exchanges where officers could receive \"military-like training\".<ref name= courthouse>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courthousenews.com/nc-city-council-accused-of-stirring-anti-semitism/|title=NC City Council Accused of Stirring Anti-Semitism|first=Erika|last=Williams|date=March 20, 2019}}</ref> The ban was first in the United States to prevent a city's police department from engaging in international training.<ref name= courthouse/> On October 4, 2018 spoke at Judea Reform Congregation about his decision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.judeareform.org/event/congregational-qa-with-mayor-steve-schewel-and-durham-city-council-members.html|title=An Evening with Mayor Schewel and Members of the Durham City Council - Event - Judea Reform Congregation|website=www.judeareform.org}}</ref> The pro-[[Zionism|Zionist]] groups North Carolina Coalition for Israel and Fight Back Now attempted to present Schewel with trophies engraved with the words \"Scapegoating Jews since 2018\" during a City Council public comment session.<ref name= wrcbtv/> Schewel responded by declining to take possession of the trophies, stating, \"Take that trophy and move it! I\u2019m -- I\u2019m gonna! You either take that trophy and move it now or you will not be coming back here to speak!\u201d<ref name= wrcbtv>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrcbtv.com/story/41820466/durham-mayor-steve-schewel-named-anti-israel-bds-mayor-of-america|title=Durham Mayor Steve Schewel Named Anti-Israel \"BDS Mayor of America\"|website=www.wrcbtv.com}}</ref> Schewel's invitation to speak at an event hosted by the Jewish Federation of Durham-Chapel Hill was rescinded in February 2020 due to his role in the police training ban.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clevelandjewishnews.com/jns/pro-israel-activists-urge-durham-jewish-federation-to-drop-mayor/article_d9aaace2-f41b-578c-ab32-7dfe980ab169.html|title=Pro-Israel activists urge Durham Jewish Federation to drop mayor with BDS ties from event|first=Sean|last=Savage|website=Cleveland Jewish News}}</ref> A complaint was filed against Schewel, the Durham City Council, and the Durham Human Relations Committee in the [[Greensboro, North Carolina|Greensboro]] federal court by the North Carolina Coalition for Israel, Rabbi Jerome Fox, Perri Shalom-Liberty, and Kathryn Wolf.<ref name= courthouse/>\n\nOn March 13, 2020 Schewel declared a [[state of emergency]] for the city of Durham, which was set to expire on March 28. The declaration was in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]], and prohibits groups of 100 people or more to meet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbs17.com/news/local-news/durham-county-news/durham-mayor-declares-state-of-emergency-for-city/|title=Durham mayor declares state of emergency for city|date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, 2020 Schewel declared a [[stay at home order]] for the city.<ref name= wral>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wral.com/durham-mayor-issues-stay-at-home-order/19028435/|title=Durham mayor issues stay-at-home order :|date=March 25, 2020|website=WRAL.com}}</ref> The order will be put in place March 26, 2020 at 6:00 PM and is issued to last until April 30, 2020.<ref name= wral/> The order bans individuals in Durham from travelling, going out in public, and prevents gatherins of more than 10 people, with some exceptions. The order closed non-essential businesses but encouraged employees to work from home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2020/03/durham-mayor-steve-schewel-stay-at-home-order-durham-april-30|title=Durham Mayor Steve Schewel issues stay-at-home order for Durham residents until April 30|website=The Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSchewel is [[Jewish]] and attends Judea Reform Congregation.<ref name= wral/><ref name= courthouse/> He has publicly opposed the organization [[Boycott, Divestment, Sanctions]], although he donated to one of its supporter groups, the [[Jewish Voice for Peace]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voice4israel.com/reform-jews-ask-durhams-mayor-steve-schewel-remove-israel-from-statement/|title=Reform Jews Ask Durham's Mayor to Remove Israel from Statement|date=October 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe is married to Lao Rubert, the former executive director of the Carolina Justice Policy Center. They have two sons and live in Durham.<ref name= hart>{{Cite web|url=https://hart.sanford.duke.edu/faculty/steve_schewel/|title=Steve Schewel \u2013 Hart Leadership Program}}</ref> He has coached soccer for middle schools and high schools in Durham.<ref name= hart/> Schewel likes to run in his free time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bullcityrunning.com/run-local-spotlight-mayor-steve-schewel/|title=Run Local Spotlight: Mayor Steve Schewel &#124; Bull City Running|website=bullcityrunning.com}}</ref>\n\nSchewel has served on as the Chair of the [[Durham Technical Community College|Durham Tech Community Foundation]] and has served on the boards of the Durham Public Education Network, the [[Durham Arts Council]], the Blue Ribbon Commission for the Future of [[Durham School of the Arts|Durham High School]], and [[Urban Ministries]] of Durham. He also served on the community advisory boards for [[WNCU]] and [[WUNC (FM)|WUNC]] radio stations.<ref name= hart/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.stevefordurham.com/ Mayoral campaign site]\n\n{{North Carolina cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schewel, Steve}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American newspaper founders]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American Reform Jews]]\n[[Category:American newspaper executives]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Jewish American academics]]\n[[Category:Jewish American people in North Carolina politics]]\n[[Category:Jewish mayors of places in the United States]]\n[[Category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:Duke University faculty]]\n[[Category:Durham, North Carolina City Council members]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Durham, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Music festival founders]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Central University faculty]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Democrats]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Lynchburg, Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politician, businessman, and academic}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = PIC Mayor Steve Schewel.jpg\n| order = \n| office = [[List of mayors of Durham, North Carolina|Mayor of Durham, North Carolina]]\n| term_start = 2017\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Bill Bell (mayor)|Bill Bell]]\n| successor = \n| office2 = Durham City Councilman\n| term_start2 = 2011\n| term_end2 = 2017\n| office3 = Vice Chair of the [[Durham Public Schools|Durham Public School Board]]\n| term_start3 = 2004\n| term_end3= 2008\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1951}}\n| birth_place = [[Lynchburg, Virginia]], US\n| alma_mater = [[Duke University]] <small>([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])</small><br>[[Columbia University]] <small>([[Master of Arts|M.A.]])</small><br>[[Duke University]] <small>([[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])</small>\n| profession = politician, academic, businessman\n| spouse = Lao Rubert\n| children = 2\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n}}\n\n'''Steve Schewel''' (born 1951) is an American politician, businessman, and academic. A [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he is the current [[List of mayors of Durham, North Carolina|Mayor]] of [[Durham, North Carolina]] and formerly served on the Durham City Council and as the Vice Chair of the [[Durham Public Schools|Durham Public School Board]]. Schewel is also a faculty member at [[Duke University]]'s [[Sanford School of Public Policy]] and a former faculty member at [[North Carolina Central University]]. He founded the weekly newspaper ''[[Indy Week]]'' in 1983, and served as its president until he sold the paper in 2012. In 2010 he co-founded the [[Hopscotch Music Festival]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSchewel grew up in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]]. He moved to North Carolina in 1969 to attend [[Duke University]]. While an undergraduate student, Schewel served as the president of the Associated Students of Duke University. In this capacity, he granted the charter to Duke's first [[LGBTQ]] student organization in 1973.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dukespace.lib.duke.edu/dspace/bitstream/handle/10161/7853/Liggett_Middlesworth-Paper.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |title=Divergent Priorities, Diverging Visions:Lesbian Separatist versus Gay Male Integrationist Ideology surrounding Duke in the 1970s and 80s |date=2013 |website=dukespace.lib.duke.edu |format=PDF|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> He graduated [[magna cum laude]] from Duke in 1973.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sanford.duke.edu/people/faculty/schewel-stephen|title=Schewel, Stephen &#124; Duke University Sanford School of Public Policy|website=sanford.duke.edu}}</ref> He earned a Master's degree in English from [[Columbia University]] in 1974, and a Ph.D. in education from Duke in 1982.<ref name= hart/>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Business and academia ===\nIn 1983 Schewel founded the newspaper ''[[Indy Week|North Carolina Independent]]'', later renamed ''Indy Week''.<ref name=\"UNC library\">{{cite web|title=Collection Number 05319: Independent Weekly Records, 1982-2004|url=http://www.lib.unc.edu/mss/inv/i/Independent_Weekly.html|work=Louis Round Wilson Special Collections Library|publisher=[[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill]]|accessdate=November 18, 2012}}</ref> Schewel personally wrote the state's first [[same-sex marriage]] announcement in the paper.<ref name= steved/> Schewel stepped down as the paper's publisher in 1999, but continued on as president of the company until he sold it in 2012.<ref name= hart/> He is also a co-founder of the [[Hopscotch Music Festival]], which he sold in 2015.<ref name= hart/>\n\nSchewel is a visiting assistant professor at [[Duke University]]\u2019s [[Sanford School of Public Policy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.heraldsun.com/news/politics-government/election/article183337776.html|title=Steve Schewel to be Durham\u2019s next mayor|last=Baumgartner Vaughan|first=Dawn|date=2017-11-07|work=The Herald-Sun|access-date=2019-12-28|url-status=live|last2=Eanes|first2=Zachery|last3=Johnson|first3=Joe}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://durhamnc.gov/1329/About-the-Mayor|title=Stephen M. Schewel &#124; Durham, NC|website=durhamnc.gov}}</ref> He is also a former [[Durham Public Schools]] board of education member and former English instructor at [[North Carolina Central University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stevefordurham.com/meet-steve|title=Meet Steve|website=Steve Schewel for Durham|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\nFrom 2004 to 2008 Schewel was a member, and Vice-Chair, of the [[Durham Public Schools]] Board of Education. He was elected to the Durham City Council in 2011 and served until 2017.<ref name= hart/> While serving on the city council, Schewel was an outspoken critic of [[North Carolina Amendment 1]] and introduced a city resolution to support [[marriage equality]]. He and his wife hosted a fundraiser at their home, raising over $200,000 to assist organizations fighting against the amendment.<ref name= steved>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stevefordurham.com/lgbtq-rights|title=LGBTQ Rights|website=Steve Schewel for Durham}}</ref>\n\nSchewel was [[2017 Durham mayoral election|elected mayor of Durham]] on November 7, 2017, to succeed the retiring [[Bill Bell (mayor)|Bill Bell]]. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wral.com/councilman-to-succeed-bell-as-durham-mayor/17098449/|title=Councilman to succeed Bell as Durham mayor :|last=|first=|date=2017-11-07|website=WRAL.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> After being sworn-in as mayor, Schewel spoke about hopes for [[gun control]] and environmental regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indyweek.com/api/content/0c23b601-f6fc-557c-9a87-15df12b9747b/|title=Six Months After Becoming Durham\u2019s Mayor, Steve Schewel Has a Lot to Say|first=Sarah|last=Willets|date=May 23, 2018|website=INDY Week}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2018 Schewel presided over the Jewish Baccalaureate Service at Duke University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://today.duke.edu/2018/05/durham-mayor-steve-schewel-addresses-jewish-baccalaureate-service|title=Durham Mayor Steve Schewel Addresses Jewish Baccalaureate Service|website=today.duke.edu}}</ref> In 2018 he participated in [[Michael Bloomberg]]'s Harvard City Leadership Initiative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytarheel.com/article/2020/03/bloomberg-local-nc-official-support|title=Bloomberg garners high-profile N.C. endorsements going into crucial Super Tuesday|website=The Daily Tar Heel}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019 Schewel joined local business leaders and the city's fire chief to address the state of industry in Durham after the [[2019 Durham gas explosion]], which affected multiple local businesses in the [[Bright Leaf Historic District]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc11.com/5264284/|title=Mayor encourages Durham residents to support local business after deadly explosion|date=April 22, 2019|website=ABC11 Raleigh-Durham}}</ref> Schewel had arrived on the scene shortly after the explosion took place.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indyweek.com/api/content/c350e0d2-6060-11e9-953a-12f1225286c6/|title=Here\u2019s What We Know\u2014And Don\u2019t Know\u2014About the Explosion That Shook Downtown Durham Last Week|first=Sarah|last=Willets|date=April 16, 2019|website=INDY Week}}</ref> \n\nSchewel proposed a $95 million housing bond in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2019/11/durham-candidates-election-city-council-mayor-municipal|title=A guide to the Durham city council and mayor candidates for Tuesday's municipal election|website=The Chronicle}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020 Schewel stated that the city intends to help fund the mitigation of carbon monoxide issues at McDougald Terrace, a public housing complex in Durham that had to evacuate its residents due to a carbon monoxide leak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc11.com/5823431/|title='It's become more urgent': Durham mayor Steve Schewel to shuffle funding for McDougald Terrace|date=January 8, 2020|website=ABC11 Raleigh-Durham}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020 Schewel was criticized by members of the [[Israel lobby in the United States]] for supporting a municipal resolution banning police training in Israel for Durham police officers. Schewel banned the program after it was alleged that the program provided military-style training and encouraged racial violence against [[African-American]] communities.<ref name= wrcbtv/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thetower.org/6641-the-israel-resolution/|title=\"The Israel Resolution\"|date=September 12, 2018|website=The Tower}}</ref> <ref name=\"Vaughan 2018\">{{cite web | last=Vaughan | first=Dawn Baumgartner | title=Bull City Politics: Jewish leaders tell council member, take Israel out of statement | website=heraldsun | date=2018-10-02 | url=https://www.heraldsun.com/news/local/counties/durham-county/article219365335.html | access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\nThe ban, approved in April 2018, forbids members of the [[Durham Police Department]] from engaging in international training exchanges where officers could receive \"military-like training\".<ref name= courthouse>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courthousenews.com/nc-city-council-accused-of-stirring-anti-semitism/|title=NC City Council Accused of Stirring Anti-Semitism|first=Erika|last=Williams|date=March 20, 2019}}</ref> The ban was first in the United States to prevent a city's police department from engaging in international training.<ref name= courthouse/> On October 4, 2018 spoke at Judea Reform Congregation about his decision.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.judeareform.org/event/congregational-qa-with-mayor-steve-schewel-and-durham-city-council-members.html|title=An Evening with Mayor Schewel and Members of the Durham City Council - Event - Judea Reform Congregation|website=www.judeareform.org}}</ref> The pro-[[Zionism|Zionist]] groups North Carolina Coalition for Israel and Fight Back Now attempted to present Schewel with trophies engraved with the words \"Scapegoating Jews since 2018\" during a City Council public comment session.<ref name= wrcbtv/> Schewel responded by declining to take possession of the trophies, stating, \"Take that trophy and move it! I\u2019m -- I\u2019m gonna! You either take that trophy and move it now or you will not be coming back here to speak!\u201d<ref name= wrcbtv>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrcbtv.com/story/41820466/durham-mayor-steve-schewel-named-anti-israel-bds-mayor-of-america|title=Durham Mayor Steve Schewel Named Anti-Israel \u201cBDS Mayor of America\u201d|website=www.wrcbtv.com}}</ref> Schewel's invitation to speak at an event hosted by the Jewish Federation of Durham-Chapel Hill was rescinded in February 2020 due to his role in the police training ban.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clevelandjewishnews.com/jns/pro-israel-activists-urge-durham-jewish-federation-to-drop-mayor/article_d9aaace2-f41b-578c-ab32-7dfe980ab169.html|title=Pro-Israel activists urge Durham Jewish Federation to drop mayor with BDS ties from event|first=Sean|last=Savage|website=Cleveland Jewish News}}</ref> A complaint was filed against Schewel, the Durham City Council, and the Durham Human Relations Committee in the [[Greensboro, North Carolina|Greensboro]] federal court by the North Carolina Coalition for Israel, Rabbi Jerome Fox, Perri Shalom-Liberty, and Kathryn Wolf.<ref name= courthouse/>\n\nOn March 13, 2020 Schewel declared a [[state of emergency]] for the city of Durham, which was set to expire on March 28. The declaration was in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]], and prohibits groups of 100 people or more to meet.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbs17.com/news/local-news/durham-county-news/durham-mayor-declares-state-of-emergency-for-city/|title=Durham mayor declares state of emergency for city|date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 25, 2020 Schewel declared a [[stay at home order]] for the city.<ref name= wral>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wral.com/durham-mayor-issues-stay-at-home-order/19028435/|title=Durham mayor issues stay-at-home order :|date=March 25, 2020|website=WRAL.com}}</ref> The order will be put in place March 26, 2020 at 6:00 PM and is issued to last until April 30, 2020.<ref name= wral/> The order bans individuals in Durham from travelling, going out in public, and prevents gatherins of more than 10 people, with some exceptions. The order closed non-essential businesses but encouraged employees to work from home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2020/03/durham-mayor-steve-schewel-stay-at-home-order-durham-april-30|title=Durham Mayor Steve Schewel issues stay-at-home order for Durham residents until April 30|website=The Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSchewel is [[Jewish]] and attends Judea Reform Congregation.<ref name= wral/><ref name= courthouse/> He has publicly opposed the organization [[Boycott, Divestment, Sanctions]], although he donated to one of it's supporter groups, the [[Jewish Voice for Peace]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://voice4israel.com/reform-jews-ask-durhams-mayor-steve-schewel-remove-israel-from-statement/|title=Reform Jews Ask Durham's Mayor to Remove Israel from Statement|date=October 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe is married to Lao Rubert, the former executive director of the Carolina Justice Policy Center. They have two sons and live in Durham.<ref name= hart>{{Cite web|url=https://hart.sanford.duke.edu/faculty/steve_schewel/|title=Steve Schewel \u2013 Hart Leadership Program}}</ref> He has coached soccer for middle schools and high schools in Durham.<ref name= hart/> Schewel likes to run in his free time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bullcityrunning.com/run-local-spotlight-mayor-steve-schewel/|title=Run Local Spotlight: Mayor Steve Schewel &#124; Bull City Running|website=bullcityrunning.com}}</ref>\n\nSchewel has served on as the Chair of the [[Durham Technical Community College|Durham Tech Community Foundation]] and has served on the boards of the Durham Public Education Network, the [[Durham Arts Council]], the Blue Ribbon Commission for the Future of [[Durham School of the Arts|Durham High School]], and [[Urban Ministries]] of Durham. He also served on the community advisory boards for [[WNCU]] and [[WUNC (FM)|WUNC]] radio stations.<ref name= hart/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.stevefordurham.com/ Mayoral campaign site]\n\n{{North Carolina cities and mayors of 100,000 population}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schewel, Steve}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American newspaper founders]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American Reform Jews]]\n[[Category:American newspaper executives]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Jewish American academics]]\n[[Category:Jewish American people in North Carolina politics]]\n[[Category:Jewish mayors of places in the United States]]\n[[category:Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Duke University alumni]]\n[[Category:Duke University faculty]]\n[[Category:Durham, North Carolina City Council members]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Durham, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Music festival founders]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Central University faculty]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Democrats]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Lynchburg, Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Neils51", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling - it's->its,typo(s) fixed: Master's degree \u2192 master's degree", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Schewel"}
{"title_page": "John Rasmussen (professor)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = John Rasmussen\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1963|03|31}}\n| birth_place        = [[Aalborg]], [[Denmark]]\n| nationality        = [[Denmark|Danish]]\n| citizenship        = [[Denmark]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Ms.c.]] & [[PhD]] from [[Aalborg University]]\n| occupation         = [[Professor]] of [[biomechanics]] at [[Aalborg University]] and [[Chief Technology Officer]] at AnyBody Technology A/S\n| employer           = [[Aalborg University]]\n| home_town          = [[Aalborg]], [[Denmark]]\n}}\n\n'''John Rasmussen''' is a [[professor]] of [[biomechanics]] at [[Aalborg University]].<ref name=\"John Rasmussen\">{{Cite web|url=https://vbn.aau.dk/en/persons/107933|title=John Rasmussen|website=Aalborg University's Research Portal|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> His research is aimed both at [[solid mechanics]], [[biomechanics]], [[biomedical engineering]] and [[sports engineering]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://login.infomedia.dk/?returnUrl=https%3a%2f%2fapps.infomedia.dk%3a443%2fmediearkiv%2f%3farticles%3de2a540fe&appname=InsightWebMs|title=Nordjyske.dk, 24th of April 2011: AAU-forskere bag bedre kn\u00e6proteser|last=|first=|date=|website=login.infomedia.dk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ing.dk/artikel/saadan-kringler-mikkel-hansen-vanvittige-skruebolde-i-kassen-165679|title=S\u00e5dan kringler Mikkel Hansen vanvittige skruebolde i kassen|last=|first=|date=|website=ing.dk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Education and research ==\nJohn Rasmussen was educated at [[Aalborg University]], where he graduated as [[Master's degree|MA]] in [[1986]], and three years later received his [[PhD]] in [[computer-aided engineering]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.biomechanics2018.wm.uz.zgora.pl/images/CV_Rasmussen.pdf|title=Curriculum Vitae of John Rasmussen|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In addition to his academic work, John Rasmussen acted as [[chief executive officer]] at AnyBody Technology A/S from [[2001]] to [[2008]] and subsequently became the [[Chief technology officer|CTO]] of the same company.<ref name=\"John Rasmussen\"/> Furthermore, Rasmussen publishes research on a personal blog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biomechanicsforeverybody.wordpress.com/|title=Biomechanics For Everybody|website=Biomechanics For Everybody|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nRasmussen's research has influenced the theoretical field of [[Structural optimization|structural optimisation]] in the late [[80s|\u00b480s]] by applying the finite element method as the engine of his research, thus enabling optimisation of practical structures rather than conducting academic examples.\n\nIn the late \u00b490s, he formed the ''AnyBody Research Project'' at [[Aalborg University]], which he is still a leading part of. One of the goals of his research is to develop methods for analysing the [[biomechanics]] of the [[human body]] involving [[bone]]s, [[joint]]s, [[muscle]]s and [[tendon]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mo.infomedia.dk/ShowArticle.aspx?Duid=e642fb24&UrlID=6b1166c7-0e52-4fb3-bb32-3c88e33110fe&Link=|title=Dyrl\u00e6ger l\u00e6rer menneskelige gigt-tricks|last=|first=|date=|website=mo.infomedia.dk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nHis research has contributed to the treatment of [[osteoarthritis]], general [[disability]] and the optimisation of sports performances.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Olesen|first=Christian Gammelgaard|last2=Rasmussen|first2=John|date=2009|title=AnyBody: Tryks\u00e5rsprojekt p\u00e5 Aalborg Universitet|url=https://vbn.aau.dk/en/publications/anybody-tryks%C3%A5rsprojekt-p%C3%A5-aalborg-universitet|journal=S\u00e5r|language=Danish|volume=17|issue=4|pages=216\u2013217|issn=0907-9513}}</ref> Furthermore, John Rasmussen has initiated a new branch of [[Interdisciplinarity|interdisciplinary]] [[biomechanics]] in cooperation with [[Aalborg University]]\u2019s Laboratory for [[Stem-cell research|Stem Cell Research]] in the [[aetiology]] of [[pressure ulcer]]s, which has led to new results in [[tissue engineering]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Researchers]]\n[[Category:Aalborg University alumni]]\n[[Category:Aalborg University]]\n[[Category:Denmark]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Aalborg University faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = John Rasmussen\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1963|03|31}}\n| birth_place        = [[Aalborg]], [[Denmark]]\n| nationality        = [[Denmark|Danish]]\n| citizenship        = [[Denmark]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Ms.c.]] & [[PhD]] from [[Aalborg University]]\n| occupation         = [[Professor]] of [[biomechanics]] at [[Aalborg University]] and [[Chief Technology Officer]] at AnyBody Technology A/S\n| employer           = [[Aalborg University]]\n| home_town          = [[Aalborg]], [[Denmark]]\n}}\n\n'''John Rasmussen''' is a [[professor]] of [[biomechanics]] at [[Aalborg University]].<ref name=\"John Rasmussen\">{{Cite web|url=https://vbn.aau.dk/en/persons/107933|title=John Rasmussen|website=Aalborg University's Research Portal|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> His research is aimed both at [[solid mechanics]], [[biomechanics]], [[biomedical engineering]] and [[sports engineering]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://login.infomedia.dk/?returnUrl=https%3a%2f%2fapps.infomedia.dk%3a443%2fmediearkiv%2f%3farticles%3de2a540fe&appname=InsightWebMs|title=Nordjyske.dk, 24th of April 2011: AAU-forskere bag bedre kn\u00e6proteser|last=|first=|date=|website=login.infomedia.dk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ing.dk/artikel/saadan-kringler-mikkel-hansen-vanvittige-skruebolde-i-kassen-165679|title=S\u00e5dan kringler Mikkel Hansen vanvittige skruebolde i kassen|last=|first=|date=|website=ing.dk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Education and research ==\nJohn Rasmussen was educated at [[Aalborg University]], where he graduated as [[Master's degree|MA]] in [[1986]], and three years later received his [[PhD]] in [[computer-aided engineering]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.biomechanics2018.wm.uz.zgora.pl/images/CV_Rasmussen.pdf|title=Curriculum Vitae of John Rasmussen|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In addition to his academic work, John Rasmussen acted as [[chief executive officer]] at AnyBody Technology A/S from [[2001]] to [[2008]] and subsequently became the [[Chief technology officer|CTO]] of the same company.<ref name=\"John Rasmussen\"/> Furthermore, Rasmussen publishes research in a personal blog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://biomechanicsforeverybody.wordpress.com/|title=Biomechanics For Everybody|website=Biomechanics For Everybody|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nRasmussen's research has influenced the theoretical field of [[Structural optimization|structural optimisation]] in the late [[80s|80's]] by applying the finite element method as the engine of his research, thus enabling optimisation of practical structures rather than conducting academic examples.\n\nIn the late 90's, he formed the ''AnyBody Research Project'' at [[Aalborg University]], which he is still a leading part of. One of the goals of his research is to develop methods for analysing the [[biomechanics]] of the [[human body]] involving [[bone]]s, [[joint]]s, [[muscle]]s and [[tendon]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mo.infomedia.dk/ShowArticle.aspx?Duid=e642fb24&UrlID=6b1166c7-0e52-4fb3-bb32-3c88e33110fe&Link=|title=Dyrl\u00e6ger l\u00e6rer menneskelige gigt-tricks|last=|first=|date=|website=mo.infomedia.dk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nHis research has contributed to the treatment of [[osteoarthritis]], general [[disability]] and to the optimisation of sports performances.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Olesen|first=Christian Gammelgaard|last2=Rasmussen|first2=John|date=2009|title=AnyBody: Tryks\u00e5rsprojekt p\u00e5 Aalborg Universitet|url=https://vbn.aau.dk/en/publications/anybody-tryks%C3%A5rsprojekt-p%C3%A5-aalborg-universitet|journal=S\u00e5r|language=Danish|volume=17|issue=4|pages=216\u2013217|issn=0907-9513}}</ref> Furthermore, John Rasmussen has initiated a new branch of [[Interdisciplinarity|interdisciplinary]] [[biomechanics]] in cooperation with [[Aalborg University]]\u2019s Laboratory for [[Stem-cell research|Stem Cell Research]]<nowiki/>h in the [[aetiology]] of [[pressure ulcer]]s, which has led to new results in [[tissue engineering]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:Researchers]]\n[[Category:Aalborg University alumni]]\n[[Category:Aalborg University]]\n[[Category:Denmark]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Aalborg University faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Randeris4", "label": "safe", "comment": "corrected grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Rasmussen_(professor)"}
